    "Beijing":  {
                    "dish":  "Peking Duck",
                    "description":  "A world-renowned dish with a history spanning over 600 years, originating from the Ming Dynasty imperial cuisine. Initially reserved for emperors, it became a symbol of prestige and refinement. Its popularity grew during the Qing Dynasty, and it has since become a cultural icon, even playing a role in diplomacy. The specific breed of duck used is the Pekin Duck, known for its mild, moist flavor. The preparation is meticulous, involving air-drying for hours to achieve a paper-thin, crispy skin. The duck is traditionally roasted in a wood-fired oven and served with thin pancakes, hoisin sauce, and slivered green onions and cucumbers.",
