    "Tianjin":  {
                    "dish":  "Jianbing Guozi (煎饼果子)",
                    "description":  "Jianbing has a history of over 2,000 years, traced back to the Three Kingdoms period in Shandong province. Legend says chancellor Zhuge Liang invented it to feed his soldiers who had lost their woks. The Tianjin style became famous and was first documented in a newspaper in 1933. Jianbing Guozi is a popular breakfast street food. The Tianjin style is famous for its use of mung bean flour for a softer crepe and is typically filled with youtiao (fried dough sticks), whereas the original Shandong version uses crispier crackers. In 2017, the skill of making Tianjin Jianbing Guozi was listed as a municipal intangible cultural heritage.",
                    "steps":  [
                                  "Prepare the Batter: Combine warm water, mung bean powder, soybean powder, and all-purpose flour in a mixing bowl. Whisk until smooth. The batter should be thick but runny. Let it rest for at least 20 minutes.",
                                  "Cook the Crepe: Heat a griddle or a non-stick pan over medium heat with a thin layer of oil. Pour about a cup of batter onto the griddle and spread it evenly in a circular motion to form a thin crepe.",
                                  "Add Egg and Toppings: Crack the eggs directly onto the crepe and spread them evenly. Before the eggs are fully cooked, sprinkle with chopped green onions and sesame seeds.",
                                  "Assemble the Jianbing: After about 10 seconds, flip the crepe. Brush the cooked surface with your sweet bean paste or hoisin sauce.",
                                  "Place the crispy crackers or youtiao in the middle.",
                                  "Fold the two sides of the crepe over the filling, then fold it in half again to create a rectangle.",
                                  "Serve immediately while hot and crispy."
                              ],
                    "ingredients":  [
                                        "For the Batter:",
                                        "2 cups warm water",
                                        "¾ cup mung bean powder",
                                        "½ cup soybean powder",
                                        "¼ cup all-purpose flour",
                                        "For the Crepe \u0026 Toppings:",
                                        "1 tbsp vegetable oil",
                                        "2 large eggs",
                                        "¼ cup chopped green onions",
                                        "2 tbsp black sesame seeds",
                                        "¼ cup sweet bean paste or hoisin sauce",
                                        "2 crispy fried crackers or 1 youtiao (fried dough stick)"
                                    ]
                },
    "Sichuan":  {
                    "dish":  "Mapo Tofu",
                    "description":  "Created in the late 19th century by a woman named Chen Ma Po (Pock-marked Grandma Chen) in Chengdu. It began as a humble dish for laborers but became the definitive example of Sichuan\u0027s \u0027Mala\u0027 (numbing and spicy) flavor profile. The soul of this dish is \u0027Pixian Doubanjiang\u0027, a fermented broad bean paste with chilies from Pixian county. Authentic versions must include Sichuan peppercorns for the signature tingling sensation.",
